Willamette River Salmon

Allison Hacker, Sydney Rilum, Elmera Azadpour

2/2/2021

Overview

Fish bypass at the Willamette Falls hydroelectric plant. Source: Portland Gas and Electric

Every year, salmon and steelhead pass make their way from the Pacific Ocean up Oregeon’s Willamette River to spawn. Fish ladders allow the fish to move past dams and give scientists an opportunity to track their numbers. Daily visual counts of adult fish were conducted at all major dams in the Columbia River basin, including Willamette Falls (see location below). This report will explore adult fish passage at Willamette Falls from 2001 to 2010.

Map of fish ladder location

Data obtained from Columbia River DART (Data Access in Real Time). Data collected by Oregon Department of Fish and Wildlife.

Daily Time Series Data

# Read in the data and clean up column names
salmon <- read_csv(here("data", "willamette_fish_passage.csv")) %>% 
  clean_names()

salmon_ts <- salmon %>% 
  mutate(date = lubridate::mdy(date)) %>%  #converts date to readable R form
  as_tsibble(key = NULL, index = date)

salmon_ds <- salmon_ts %>% 
  select(date,coho,jack_coho,steelhead)  %>% 
  replace(is.na(.), 0) %>% 
  pivot_longer(cols = coho:steelhead, #pivoted longer to 
  names_to = "species" ,
  values_to = "count")

ggplot(salmon_ds, aes(date, count)) +
  geom_line(aes(color = species)) +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(x = "Year", y = "Adult fish count") +
  scale_color_discrete(name = "Fish Species",
                       breaks = c("coho", "jack_coho", "steelhead"),
                       labels = c("Coho", "Jack Coho", "Steelhead"))+
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::comma)

Figure 1. Time series plot for coho, jack coho, and steelhead salmon species counts at the Willamette Falls fish ladder on the Willamette River in Oregon from years 2001 to 2010. Red line indicates times series counts for Coho, green line for Jack coho and blue line for Steelhead. Data source: Oregon Department of Fish and Wildlife.

Major trends:

  • Jack coho adult count is low in comparison to Coho and Steelhead through the time series.

  • Steelhead adult count appears to be greatest compared to Coho and Jack coho up until later in the year in 2009 calendar year. This similar increase occurs later in 2010 as well.

Seasonplots

# Convert salmon data set into a time series data frame (tsibble)
salmon_ts <- salmon %>% 
  mutate(date = lubridate::mdy(date)) %>%  #converts date to readable R form
  as_tsibble(key = NULL, index = date)

# Create seasonplots
coho_season <- salmon_ts %>% 
  gg_season(y = coho) +
  labs(y = "Coho",
       x = "",
       title = "Salmon Seasonplots")

jack_coho_season <- salmon_ts %>% 
  gg_season(y = jack_coho) +
  labs(y = "Jack Coho",
       x = "")

steelhead_season <- salmon_ts %>% 
  gg_season(y = steelhead) +
  labs(y = "Steelhead",
       x = "Month")

# Combine seasonplots into a single compound figure using the `patchwork` package
coho_season / jack_coho_season / steelhead_season &
  theme_light() +
  theme(legend.position = "none")

Figure 2. Seasonplots for coho, jack coho, and steelhead salmon species counts at the Willamette Falls fish ladder on the Willamette River in Oregon. Each colored line represents count data for a single year, including the years 2001 to 2010. Data source: Oregon Department of Fish and Wildlife.

Major Trends:

  • Coho and jack coho salmon are only present from late August to early November, with counts peaking in the month of October.

  • Steelhead salmon are present year-round, with counts highest in the spring (from March to June) and lowest in the fall.

Summary Statistics and Analysis

salmon_count <- salmon_ds %>% 
  index_by(year = ~ year(.)) %>% 
  group_by(species) %>% 
  summarise(total_count = sum(count))

ggplot(data = salmon_count, aes(x = year, y = total_count, color = species))+
  geom_line()+
  geom_point()+
  theme_minimal()+
  labs(x = "Year", y = "Adult fish count")+
  scale_color_discrete(name = "Fish Species",
                       breaks = c("coho", "jack_coho", "steelhead"),
                       labels = c("Coho", "Jack Coho", "Steelhead"))+
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = 2001:2010)+
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::comma)

Figure 3. Annual count of adult coho (red), jack coho (green), and steelhead (blue) observed at the Willamette Falls fish ladder on the Willamette River from 2001 to 2010. Data source: Oregon Department of Fish and Wildlife.

Major Trends:

  • Annual counts of jack coho, the least common species, have remained relatively constant from 2001-2010.

  • Annual counts of coho were only slightly higher than jack coho until 2009 when they increased markedly.

  • Steelhead counts had the greatest interannual variation. Steelhead was the only species that exhibited a downward trend in annual count.
